AU  - ROSA, NA
AU  - NAPSTAD, DC
AU  - BAKK, A
TI  - DIAMETRICAL STRUCTURE AND BRIEF ECOLOGICAL ECONOMICAL CHARACTERIZATION OF THE 108 TREE SPECIES OF THE BRAZILIAN AMAZON FOREST
T2  - INTERCIENCIA
AB  - Twenty-one botanical stocks, of one hectare each, were inventoried, in the States of Para (17), Maranhao (3) and Rondonia (1).  In total, 10,257 individuals were registered, with diameter at breast height (DBH) > or < 10 cm. belonging to 790 species, distributed among 68 families.  One hundred and eight species (14% of the total) presented 20 or more individuals, totalizing 7,011 (68%) individuals; these species are analyzed in the present paper in relation to:  1) growth in diameter and thickness of the trunk, 2) vertical stratification, 3) natural regeneration and 4) usefulness of the species.
   The individuals of each of the 108 species were grouped in 5 classes according to growth of the trunk, namely:  a) Small (DBH < 30 cm.) 45 (42%) species; b) Medium, between 30 and 70 cm. 43 (40%) species; c) 5 (5%) species; d) very big DBH (between 100 and 200 cm.) 5 (4%) species and e) Giant (DBH > 200 cm.) 2 (2%) species.
   The vertical stratification, obeys the following criteria:  a) emerging (total height greater than 40 m.) 6 (6%) species; b) Bunting (height between 25 and 40 m.), 54 (50%) species and, c) sub forest (height less than 10m) 2 (2%) species.
   Natural regeneration, analyzed with respect to the availability of light, allowed us to classify the 108 species studied in three distinct groups:  a) Full sunthey regenerate in open environments - total 43 (40%) species; b) wood clearing - need direct light for part of the day, 100 (93%) species and shadow - regenerate only in the absence of direct light, 8 (7%) species.
   The present usefulness of the species was approached under two large groups:  value of the wood and non-wood use(s).  The species with wood value were grouped under the following categories:  a) Very high value (m3 sawed wood:  greater than U.S. $400.00) no species were registered in this category; b) High value, 16 species registered (15%); c) medium value, 16 (15%) species were registered and d) low value (m3 of sawed wood less than U.S. $80.00) 38 (35%) species.  Of the 108 species studied, 38 (35%) had at present no value in the internal and external markets.  The non-wood uses are:  a) food for man and fauna, (10 species); b) food exclusively for the fauna, (85 species); c) fiber providers, (13 species); d) medical application, (12 species); e) production of gum, latex or essential oil (8.8 and 9 species) respectively; f) cellulose industry, (5 species); g) ornamental use, (4 species); h) trunk bark with anti-corrosive properties, (1 species); aromatic, (1 species); and silicose, (1 species); application with tincture (2 species); and venomous substance for cattle, (1 species).
   Finally, various comments are made on the most characteristic species of the humid dense Amazonian Forest.
